# ============================================================
# D1: Tool Use Under the Hood
# ============================================================
# This demo shows the difference between LLMs with and without tools.
# Run each part in order. See demo-script.md for talking points.
#
# Prerequisites:
#   - VS Code with REST Client extension
#   - OPENAI_API_KEY in .env file
# ============================================================

@openai-key={{$processEnv OPENAI_API_KEY}}
@model=gpt-5.4

# ============================================================
# PART 1: Without Tools — the model can only guess
# ============================================================
# TALKING POINT: This is a raw API call. No tools, no agent
# framework. The model can only predict tokens. Watch what
# comes back when we ask about something it can't know.
# ============================================================

### Part 1: LLM without tools
POST https://api.openai.com/v1/chat/completions
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{openai-key}}

{
  "model": "{{model}}",
  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "What's the current weather like in San Francisco? I need the temperature and conditions."
    }
  ]
}

# ============================================================
# PART 2: With a tool definition — the model asks for help
# ============================================================
# TALKING POINT: Same question, same model. We only added a
# tool definition — a JSON schema. Watch how the response
# changes from text to a structured tool_call.
# ============================================================

### Part 2: LLM with tool definition
POST https://api.openai.com/v1/chat/completions
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{openai-key}}

{
  "model": "{{model}}",
  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "What's the current weather like in San Francisco? I need the temperature and conditions."
    }
  ],
  "tools": [
    {
      "type": "function",
      "function": {
        "name": "get_weather",
        "description": "Get current weather information for a specified city",
        "parameters": {
          "type": "object",
          "properties": {
            "city": {
              "type": "string",
              "description": "The city name, e.g. San Francisco"
            },
            "units": {
              "type": "string",
              "enum": ["celsius", "fahrenheit"],
              "description": "Temperature units"
            }
          },
          "required": ["city"]
        }
      }
    }
  ],
  "tool_choice": "auto"
}

# ============================================================
# PART 3: Complete the loop — feed tool results back
# ============================================================
# TALKING POINT: In a real agent, something would call the
# weather API. We simulate it with mock data. The model takes
# the raw JSON and produces a grounded, natural response.
#
# This is the full agent loop in miniature:
#   1. User asks a question
#   2. Model requests a tool call (assistant role, tool_calls)
#   3. Something executes the tool (tool role, result)
#   4. Model uses the result to answer
# ============================================================

### Part 3: Send tool results back
POST https://api.openai.com/v1/chat/completions
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{openai-key}}

{
  "model": "{{model}}",
  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "What's the current weather like in San Francisco? I need the temperature and conditions."
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": null,
      "tool_calls": [
        {
          "id": "call_abc123",
          "type": "function",
          "function": {
            "name": "get_weather",
            "arguments": "{\"city\": \"San Francisco\", \"units\": \"fahrenheit\"}"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "role": "tool",
      "tool_call_id": "call_abc123",
      "content": "{\"location\": \"San Francisco, CA\", \"temperature\": 68, \"condition\": \"partly cloudy\", \"humidity\": 72, \"wind_speed\": 12}"
    }
  ]
}

# ============================================================
# PART 4: Add a system prompt — steer tone and persona
# ============================================================
# TALKING POINT: Same question, same tool result. The only
# thing we changed is a new message with role "system" at the
# top of the conversation. System prompts set the ground rules
# for the model — persona, tone, format, constraints — before
# the user ever says anything. This is the simplest form of
# context engineering: you're not changing the model, you're
# changing the context it reasons over.
# ============================================================

### Part 4: Same loop, with a system prompt
POST https://api.openai.com/v1/chat/completions
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer {{openai-key}}

{
  "model": "{{model}}",
  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "system",
      "content": "You are a dramatic 19th-century sea captain. Report all weather as if it directly threatens your ship. Use nautical language and be theatrical. Keep responses to 2-3 sentences."
    },
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "What's the current weather like in San Francisco? I need the temperature and conditions."
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": null,
      "tool_calls": [
        {
          "id": "call_abc123",
          "type": "function",
          "function": {
            "name": "get_weather",
            "arguments": "{\"city\": \"San Francisco\", \"units\": \"fahrenheit\"}"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "role": "tool",
      "tool_call_id": "call_abc123",
      "content": "{\"location\": \"San Francisco, CA\", \"temperature\": 68, \"condition\": \"partly cloudy\", \"humidity\": 72, \"wind_speed\": 12}"
    }
  ]
}

# ============================================================
# DEBRIEF
# ============================================================
# "The model didn't learn about weather. We gave it a tool,
# it decided to use it, we executed the tool, and fed the
# result back. That loop — observe, decide, act, evaluate —
# is the foundation of every agent. Claude Code, Copilot,
# Cursor — they're all running this loop with more tools
# and more iterations."
# ============================================================
